post_text: Congratulations to Jordan Champlin our CHS JAG Specialist. Jordan was awarded another national award this year during the JAG National Training Seminar. This year she was awarded the JAG National “Excellence in PBL” award. This award was given to three specialists in the national organization that contributed a high quality PBL to the JAG National PBL Library. Jordan was asked to contribute her “Respite Room” PBL. This is and exceptional honor for our Concordia program to be recognized on the national level again! Along with this award Jordan's JAG program received the 5 of 5 national award again. The 5 of 5 award is the highest award a program can receive nationally and is based around exceeding performance outcomes. On a state level, Jordan also received the Region 3 PBL of the year award. Congratulations to Jordan as we are blessed to have our hometown students back in our community impacting our local school, community, state, and country!

The 5 of 5 award is the highest award a program can receive nationally and is based around exceeding performance outcomes. On a state level, Jordan also received the Region 3 PBL of the year award. Thank you for your continued support. #constrong #wegotthis

post_text:
CAP Families,
We have been in contact with the Health Department regarding CAP attending the Concordia Municipal Pool on June 23. CAP was present from 1:00 pm until 3:00 pm on Tuesday, June 23rd. Therefore, we do not have to quarantine and will continue with our current safety protocols that are in place. CAP will remain open. However, if your child did go to the pool during the times listed below, we ask that your child does not attend CAP and follow the suggested recommendations. Thank you for your continued support.
shared_text:
1390 KNCK
June 26 at 12:26 PM ·

JUST ANNOUNCED:
The Cloud County Health Department recommends anyone who attended the Concordia Municipal Swimming Pool between the hours of 12 pm to 7 pm on Monday, June 22nd and 3:45 pm to 6:30 pm on Tuesday, June 23rd put themselves in self-quarantine for 14 days from that day due to possible exposure.

During a conference call with media members on Friday, Cloud County Health Administrator Brandi Bray said one of the nine active COVID-19 cases in the county involves an individual who worked at the Concordia Municipal Swimming Pool on June 22nd and June 23rd.

Wildside Creative is at Concordia Junior-Senior High School.
April 23 at 4:17 PM · Concordia, KS ·

We have gotten several messages about the Senior signs at the high school, mainly questions about purchasing one for the house.

When we donated these, the intention is to have them at the school for a week or two and then the seniors should grab them and take them home to display in their own yards. We do not want compensated for them directly, if you feel the need to pay for them, please donate whatever you desire to the Cloud County Resource Center or the new Caring for Cloud County program.

2020 CHS Seniors - We are Proud of You!

Kindergarten graduates: We are sure you have seen your signs also, we are still working on the rest of them, we have been a little busy and will let you all know when they are ready.

2020 Kindergarten Grads - We are Proud of You!

post_text:
USD 333 Staff will be participating in a caravan across the city of Concordia on Thursday, April 23, 2020 beginning at 5:30pm. We would love the chance to wave hello to our families and friends as we drive by. Below is the route we will be following. We will begin by the City Ballfields and then will go across town (basically covering the east side and then the west side) ending by the Broadway Plaza. We will not be able to drive up and down every street in Concordia due to time, however we have designated 4 locations where you can park and wave to us. If you choose to go to the CES parking lot, please park in the stalls as we will be following the pick-up/drop-off route. Families are also invited to walk to the closest block to wave if we are not traveling on your street. Please practice social distancing if you choose to participate in this activity. Safety first!

Also, bus drivers will run their normal route beginning at 4pm to wave to our country families.

We hope all are doing well and we can't wait to see you! #concordiastrong #wegotthis

post_text:
Food Delivery/Pick-up Updates
1. Starting Monday, we only need to see every child getting a meal one more time. We will then give you a "card" to hang in your car with the number of meals needed each day. Number of meals = number of kids we see. Once you have the card, you don't have to bring the kids to the site - just the card.
2. Please RSVP each day you need a meal by filling out the online form (see below) or by calling 785-243-3518 . This helps us prepare enough meals.
3. Meals are for ANY child ages 1-18. They do not have to attend USD 333 to get a meal.
4. Delivery is from 11:30-12:30 - first come, first serve
5. Meals are served Monday - Wednesday. On Wednesday, each child will receive 3 breakfasts and 3 lunches.
6. Again please complete the online form so we can plan accordingly with the correct number of meals at each location or call 785-243-3518.
Meal Form:
https://forms.gle/JJ3p8a8HHKsBJFWs7

To help with finding our locations we have created a interactive google map with all of our feeding sites.

https://drive.google.com/open…

SBA Coronavirus Pandemic Disaster Loans Comparison - Google Drive

CloudCorp
April 3 at 1:41 PM ·

Attached is a helpful matrix that you can use to better understand the various SBA disaster assistance programs. The matrix was created by the ASBDC to help SBDC clients understand the general parameters of the programs. We are still waiting for specific guidance and final regs from the IRS etc. governing the programs – so, this is not an official SBA document.

post_text: We are updating our meal delivery next week! You will still get 5 breakfast and 5 lunches but we are only delivering on Monday, Tuesday and Wednesday. Read below for more details. Thanks for your continued support. Remember, ANY child, age 1-18 qualifies for the free meals!
shared_text:

USD 333 "GRAB & GO" Form

Concordia Elementary School
March 27 at 5:15 PM ·

We are excited to be able to still be providing meals for the children of our community. Starting Monday, we are going to be making a few changes to our delivery schedule. You will still be getting 5 lunches and 5 breakfasts for the week, however, now we will only be delivering Monday - Wednesday.

On Monday and Tuesday you will receive 1 breakfast and 1 lunch each day. On Wednesday, you will receive 3 breakfast and 3 lunches (enough food for the rest of the week).

We ask that you still call the BOE office or fill out the form by 9AM each day you are wanting a meal. On Wednesday, you will be signing up for meals for Wednesday through Friday. On the sign up for Wednesday, just put the number of meals needed for one day and then we will triple the order on our end. By calling in or signing up on-line, you are helping us get a better headcount of how many meals we are needing for each site.

Thank you for your continued support of USD 333.

post_text:
Good News! We have now been approved to offer meal pickup for children Ages 1-18 at Jamestown and Aurora. Starting tomorrow, Wednesday, March 18, families can begin picking up meals from 11:30am-12:30pm at Jamestown Community Center, Aurora Post Office, CHS -10th St. Gazebo, 2nd Street Park, Hood Park or the Community Service Center (CAP) on 7th Street. This service will be available Monday-Friday until further notice.

A Couple of Reminders:
1. By 9AM each day please call the BOE office at 785-243-3518 OR complete the online form (see link below) to help us get an estimate of how many meals to prepare. We do need your numbers every day you plan on getting food.
2. Meals are first come, first serve
3. Wednesday you will receive lunch only
4. Starting Thursday, you will receive lunch and breakfast for the next morning
5. Meals will be available from 11:30am-12:30pm Monday-Friday until further notice.

Online form: https://forms.gle/KvaevQBFRnmYMGxH9

Thank you USD 333 staff for helping prepare the meals!

post_text:
Good Evening Patrons! We just finished an update with Commissioner Watson and other state officials. Please see below for his recommendation.

USD #333 will adhere to the recommendation and close school for the week of March 16th-20th. CAP will also be closed at this time. All activities and athletic practices will be cancelled next week. Also, any outside usage of USD 333 facilities will be cancelled for this week.

A message and letter will also be sent to families via school messenger soon.
shared_text:
Randy Watson
March 15 at 4:33 PM ·

As of Sunday, March 15, Kansas Education Commissioner Dr. Randy Watson strongly recommends that those schools currently coming off of spring break, suspend operations for the week March 16-20. All schools scheduled for spring break the week of March 16-20 will continue as planned. For schools who have spring break later in time, Commissioner Watson is strongly recommending they also close schools for the period of March 16-20.

Closing all schools during this same period of time provides Kansas officials the time needed to finalize a comprehensive plan for how to address COVID-19.

It is critical that we all follow a coordinated response to this situation.

As of Sunday, March 15, Kansas Education Commissioner Dr. Randy Watson strongly recommends that those schools currently coming off of spring break, suspend operations for the week March 16-20. All schools scheduled for spring break the week of March 16-20 will continue as planned. For schools who have spring break later in time, Commissioner Watson is strongly recommending they also close schools for the period of March 16-20.

Closing all schools during this same period of time provides Kansas officials the time needed to finalize a comprehensive plan for how to address COVID-19.

It is critical that we all follow a coordinated response to this situation.

Dear USD 333 Families,
Due to some significant illness in all of our campuses, this is a good time to talk with your children about good hand washing, coughing into the sleeve and keeping hands away from mouth, nose and eyes. Also, here are some general guidelines to follow to determine when a child should stay home from school.

· Temperature 100.0 or higher

· Vomiting within the past 24 hours

· Having frequent diarrhea stools

· Difficulty Breathing

· Open sores that are draining

· White part of the eye is red

· Child has an unexplained rash

· Persistent coughing

· Your child acts or looks sick

In these events we ask that you keep your child home for 24 hours’ fever and symptom free, without any use of medication, before returning to school. If your child is needing antibiotics for infection prescribed by a physician, we ask for your child to be on that medication for 24 hours before returning to school with a doctor’s note.

post_text:
USD 333 is very excited to host the Kansas Supreme Court in April. This session will provide a great learning opportunity for our students and community.

The Kansas Supreme Court will conduct a special evening session April 7 in Concordia as part of its ongoing outreach to familiarize people with the Kansas judiciary.

The court will be in session from 6:30 p.m. to about 8 p.m. Tuesday, April 7, in the Concordia High School auditorium, 436 W 10th St.

It will be the Supreme Court’s first visit to Concordia in the court’s 159-year history, and it will be only the 12th time that the court will hear cases in the evening.

The public is invited to attend the special session to observe the court as it hears oral arguments in two cases to be announced soon. After the hearing concludes, the justices will greet the public in an informal reception in the commons outside the auditorium. Additional Information can be found at the following link.
https://www.kscourts.org/newsroom

Good Morning USD 333,

UPDATE!!!!!!!!!!

There will be no school for USD 333, Concordia Tuesday January 14, 2020 due to the weather and extremely hazardous road conditions due to low visibility, especially concerning our county blacktop routes. Thank you for your continued support as USD 333 staff and administration work hard to put student safety first. Again no school for USD 333 Concordia on Tuesday January 14, 2020. Please stay tuned to KNCK radio and the USD 333 website and facebook pages for updated information on the rescheduling of activities.

Rationale: We tried to buy some time with a late start to see if the fog would subside. The fog remains, and is continuing to freeze on the roads making the non treated blacktops and sand surfaces very slick. Although late start buys us a couple more hours, the temperature looks to stay below freezing until 11 and our buses depart 2 hours before school begins and the call needs to be made now for food service and transportation. Nobody wins, in weather calls, but we appreciate your support as we do our best for education and safety.

post_text:
Good Afternoon,

USD 333 will dismiss school at Normal time. There will be no Afterschool Activities, CAP or Sports Practices due to the weather conditions.
Rationale: Sources for the Kansas Highway Patrol and the National Weather Service believe conditions will not deteriorate any further from their current state by our normal dismissal time. Conditions are currently very slick due to the freezing drizzle and it is our belief that an early dismissal will not benefit the safety of our students and staff drivers as well as our bus route riders. Parents that feel strongly about having their child home immediately in the current weather conditions are welcome to pick up and sign their child out, however buses will run at normal time and student drivers will not be dismissed until normal dismissal time.
Thank you for your support of our difficult weather decisions.

post_text:
January is School Board Appreciation Month.
We are saying a special thank you to the seven men and women who serve on our local school board. They volunteer their time to come to meetings, read reports and research and listen to presentations so that they can make the decisions need to keep our local schools strong. Please “share” and “like” to say thank you to these local unsung heroes! Mark Nordell 4 Years of Service, Tony Miller 4 Years of Service, Mary Beth Smith 18 Years of Service, John Culley, 4 Years of Service, Kevin Pounds 12 Years of Service, Tim Beims 4 Years of Service and Bryan Bombardier beginning his first term on January 13, 2020.
#Concordiaproud

post_text: Due to School cancellations in other school districts on Monday, and the need to reschedule a number of 7-12 school activities that impact USD 333, the Concordia Jr/Sr High School Band and Vocal Music Program has been rescheduled for Wednesday evening at 7:00PM, December 18, 2019. USD 333's practice is to not schedule school activities on Wednesday evenings, however due to significant scheduling challenges we were unable to avoid this schedule conflict. We will begin with the High School Choir and adjust the schedule accordingly to accommodate JH students returning from the League Basketball Tournament Marysville. Every decision is thoughtfully examined as we try to meet the needs of our students who are all highly involved in all of our programs. Thank you for your support.
text: Due to School cancellations in other school districts on Monday, and the need to reschedule a number of 7-12 school activities that impact USD 333, the Concordia Jr/Sr High School Band and Vocal Music Program has been rescheduled for Wednesday evening at 7:00PM, December 18, 2019. USD 333's practice is to not schedule school activities on Wednesday evenings, however due to significant scheduling challenges we were unable to avoid this schedule conflict. We will begin with the High School Choir and adjust the schedule accordingly to accommodate JH students returning from the League Basketball Tournament Marysville. Every decision is thoughtfully examined as we try to meet the needs of our students who are all highly involved in all of our programs. Thank you for your support.

post_text: "The Heart of it All" Concordia Elementary Principal Derek Holmes, and Director of Curriculum and Instruction, Krystal Breese presented "The Heart of it All" this past week at the Annual Kansas Association of Elementary School Principals Conference in Wichita. Concordia Elementary's progressive mindset developed a soft skills curriculum and social-emotional support system recognized across the region and state with our daily morning assemblies, peer model mixed grade level lunches, and mixed grade level Panther Pride extended classroom activities. Concordia Elementary's innovative staff and counselors were recognized during the presentation paving the way for our student success. #concordiaproud

November 8, 2019 at 9:01 AM ·

The Kansas Association of Secondary School Principals (KASSP) is proud to recognize Derek Holmes, Concordia Elementary/Middle School, as the KASSP Area III Middle Level Principal of the Year.

KASSP is an organization of over 450 secondary school principals from across the state of Kansas. Holmes was nominated and selected by peer principals. Candidates are evaluated on their school leadership, school improvement, dedication, professionalism, and service to students.

Congratulations are extended from the Kansas Association of Secondary School Principals to Derek Holmes.

Concordia, KS Alumni and Friends
November 5, 2019 at 4:09 PM ·

A few pictures from our mentor day. We have many more groups but thought we would share a few each time.

Freshman Topic - Academic, Extracurricular, and Personal Goals. How to achieve goals. Eliminating Timewasters.
Sophomore Topic - Developing their own brand. Responsibility and reputation. Financial Responsibility and planning for the future.
Junior Topic - Self Discovery. Important traits in friends. Valuable traits in self. How do those traits transfer to school, workplace, etc?
Senior Topic - Prepare for Senior Interview Day on November 20th. Discussed resume, dress attire, and interviewee skills and traits.

post_text: Please bundle up tomorrow morning. School doors will open at 7:25 AM. Please send your child out the door to the bus or to their respective building with a coat as we anticipate a significant cold blast tomorrow. Please refrain from dropping your child off at 7:00AM in the cold temperatures as the schools do not have staff on duty for supervision at the buildings until 7:25 AM. Thank you for helping keep all students safe!

Concordia, KS Alumni and Friends
October 8, 2019 at 3:39 PM ·

Special thanks to Cloud County Community College for sponsoring the CHS Career Day. Students will be fed a breakfast, sponsored by CCCC, while listening to student leaders talk about the various activities and clubs they can join.
After the 30 minute assembly, students will attend their Career sessions which they enrolled in last week.
While 8th-12th graders listen to our guest speakers on campus, 7th-graders will be attending a Career/Community bus tour with visits to CCCC, Cloud County Health Center, and a tour with CloudCorp of downtown businesses.

shared_text:
Concordia Elementary School is with Candace Lister.
October 1, 2019 at 9:02 PM ·

Today our CES students ran their last mile to complete a full marathon, or 26.2 miles. We are so proud of the hard-work, dedication and determination the students portrayed over the last six weeks. Thank you to the families who were committed to getting the students to school early each day. A huge thank you to our volunteers, Rod Stacken, Stacie LaBarge, JoDee Rothfuss and Kristin Will for checking the students in each day. We appreciate the sponsorship from F&A, Short Stop, Central National Bank, Funk Pharmacy, Cloud County CO-OP, and Champlin Tire Recycling that helped make the marathon possible. Thank you to the CHS athletes and CCCC for supporting our students. Lastly, thanks to Mr. Haden for all his hard work organizing and running another successful School Marathon!

Concordia, KS Alumni and Friends
September 27, 2019 at 1:05 PM ·

Earlier this year, Mrs. Retter fundraised to build a coffee bar for CHS students. Many of our alumni donated to the project so wanted to give an update. Today was the grand opening for the coffee bar in the CHS Library. It's been nonstop traffic.

CHS Students hanging out at the new coffee bar and doing some sign work welcoming the CHS Alumni.
The tour down memory lane is at 1:00 tomorrow. Meet at the CHS 10th street doors.

shared_text:
Concordia Panthers Tennis
September 26, 2019 at 10:18 PM ·

This is the first time the Concordia Girls have won the Concordia Invitational in ... well Russell and I are going to have to do some serious research ... but it’s been a while! Riley took 1st in #2 Singles, Bethanie (Ace) and Nicole took 1st in #2 Doubles, Arista Bombardier took 2nd in #1 Singles, and Ciara & Macy took 4th in #1 Doubles. We want to thank everyone who came out to watch and support us but we especially want to thank Coach Montoya for coming out and supporting us this year. We love honey sticks!
